language Essence 1.3

$ Social Golfers Problem — Formulation 5: Matrix of Sets
$
$ Domain:  matrix indexed by [int(1..w), int(1..g)] of set (size s) of Golfers
$
$ Information carried by the domain:
$   - Each cell is a set of exactly s golfers (group size enforced)
$   - Weeks and groups are indexed by integers
$
$ Information NOT carried (must be constrained explicitly):
$   - Disjointness: golfers within a week must not overlap across groups
$   - Coverage: every golfer must appear in some group each week
$   Together these form the partition constraint, which is no longer implicit.
$
$ Explicit constraints needed:
$   1. Partition constraint: groups within each week form a partition of Golfers
$   2. Pairing constraint: no two golfers share a group more than once
$
$ Compared to Formulations 1–4:
$   - The partition type is decomposed into individual sets.
$   - Group size is still carried by set (size s), but disjointness and
$     coverage must now be stated explicitly.
$   - Both week and group indices are exposed, introducing group-ordering
$     symmetry within each week.

given w, g, s : int(1..)

letting nGolfers be g * s
letting Golfers be new type of size nGolfers

find sched : matrix indexed by [int(1..w), int(1..g)] of set (size s) of Golfers

$ Partition constraint: within each week, each golfer is in exactly one group.
$ Since each group has size s and there are g groups and g*s golfers,
$ disjointness alone suffices to guarantee full coverage.
such that
    forAll i : int(1..w) .
        forAll j1 : int(1..g) .
            forAll j2 : int(1..g) .
                j1 < j2 -> |sched[i, j1] intersect sched[i, j2]| = 0,

$ Pairing constraint: no two golfers share a group more than once
such that
    forAll p1 : Golfers .
        forAll p2 : Golfers .
            p1 != p2 ->
            (sum i : int(1..w) .
                sum j : int(1..g) .
                    toInt(p1 in sched[i, j] /\ p2 in sched[i, j])
            ) <= 1
